      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "body": "1 cup nuts (optional).",
          "tone": "info",
          "title": "Also"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Cream the butter, brown sugar, and caster sugar together until pale and fluffy, three or four minutes by stand mixer or vigorous hand whisk.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Beat in the eggs one at a time, then the vanilla. The mixture should look glossy.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "In a separate bowl, whisk the flour, cornflour, bicarb, and salt together. Tip into the wet mix and fold until just combined, stop the moment the flour disappears.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Fold in the chocolate chunks (and walnuts if using). The cornflour is doing the work for the chewy texture, so don't over-mix.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Cover the bowl and chill in the fridge for at least 30 minutes, overnight if you have the time. Cold dough holds its shape and spreads less.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Heat the oven to 180°C (fan). Line two baking trays with baking paper.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Scoop heaped tablespoons of dough onto the trays, leaving a good four centimetres between each. They spread.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Bake for 11 to 13 minutes. Pull them out when the edges look set but the middles still look slightly underdone. They finish on the hot tray.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Leave to cool on the tray for five minutes before transferring to a wire rack.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": "A few of the more common issues, and what tends to fix them.",
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Drain juicy fruit, toss with a tablespoon of cornflour, or blind-bake the base before filling. A sprinkle of semolina on the base soaks up stray juice.",
              "cause": "Filling too wet, or no blind-bake.",
              "symptom": "Pastry base went soggy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Rub butter into flour to coarse breadcrumb texture, then chill the mix before scattering. Keep clumps the size of peas for crunch.",
              "cause": "Butter melted in fully before baking.",
              "symptom": "Crumble topping went sandy, not crunchy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use a deeper dish next time and bake on a tray to catch drips.",
              "cause": "Tin too small, or too much liquid.",
              "symptom": "Filling spilled over the edges"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Let chilled pies sit at room temperature for 20 minutes before baking. Bake on the middle shelf at 180°C.",
              "cause": "Tin too cold from the fridge, or oven too hot.",
              "symptom": "Top browned but middle is cold"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "If something goes wrong"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Variations",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Mixed fruit: use whatever's in season, apple plus blackberry, plum plus pear, rhubarb plus strawberry.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Nutty crumble: replace 30 g of the flour with rolled oats or chopped almonds.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make ahead, freezing, leftovers",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Best fresh. Leftovers keep two days in the fridge; reheat covered with a splash of liquid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A classic American home recipe, generous, comforting, made for a crowd. The proportions are heartier than the British equivalent; the method is built for a Sunday afternoon.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
